Notes / decisions:
  - Adapter uses direct fetch instead of `composio_call` worker tool
    or shared ComposioClient — adapters live inside the cron-kicker
    Lambda bundle which doesn't have the worker tool registry or the
    composio audit/cache stack initialized. Direct fetch keeps the
    Lambda bundle small and avoids accidentally writing to
    external_action_audit for read-only polling reads.
  - Range is A1:Z (not A<start_row>:Z as the literal spec wording
    suggested). Two reasons: (1) including row 1 lets the adapter
    grab the header row in a single round-trip; (2) row_number is
    derived as absolute spreadsheet row (i+1 where rows are 0-indexed
    from A1), so the math stays correct regardless of where data
    starts. This matches D.5's pickInputMapper for googlesheets which
    expects `row_number` to be the absolute spreadsheet row.
  - countNonEmptyRows uses "last non-empty index + 1" rather than a
    naive non-empty count. This discards trailing padding (Sheets API
    returns up to 1000 rows for a range query against a partially-
    filled sheet, mostly empty) WITHOUT collapsing internal gap rows
    — a row with operator-typed-then-deleted content stays in the
    count. Acceptable per spec.
  - header_row in state: only stored when cfg.hasHeader (start_row > 1
    OR explicit cfg.header_row !== false). Kicker's buildInputs uses
    it to build keyed `row` object; absent it falls back to
    col_0/col_1/... positional keys.
